Speaking about Aquamarine and Graves, Meg Duffy said “They shift the way I see myself and how I contextualize myself in the world. Especially my mom’s death and how I was interacting with it as a child versus how I interact with it now, and how that encompasses and informs, deeply, how I think of myself.”

https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/hand-habits/hand-habits-interview-fun-house-no-difference/

And I didn’t know she played guitar
 ’Til I turned twenty seven
 My distant cousin sent
 A box of memory

For Paste Magazine, Meg Duffy said their album Fun House was about “this period of trying to make sense of my life, I was turning over these boxes of memories that I had never really allowed myself to think about. Specifically about my mother passing away when I was young, it’s made its way into my songs before, but not in such a palpable way. I allowed myself to say things that I think, in the past, I would have been too afraid to even think about.”
